        'The Sangai was believed extinct until 1953, when a handful were rediscovered on Loktak Lake. Conservation brought the population from near-zero to about 260 — but all 260 depend on the same fragile floating habitat.',
        'Loktak Lake’s Keibul Lamjao National Park is the world’s only **floating** national park — the entire protected area rises and falls with the water level. It was designated a Ramsar Wetland of International Importance in 1990.',
        'Champu Khangpok, a village on Loktak Lake, is built entirely on phumdis. Families live in houses on floating islands, growing vegetables and fishing from their front doors — a community literally living on water.',
